trainControl

  • pro: quick, painless, ready to go in a few minutes
  • pro: highly customizable
  • pro: mistakes and leaks are easy to spot
  • con: ?

trainControl code

#downSample to create a balanced problem
data <- downSample(Alzheimers, Alzheimers$response)

#create a vector with predictors
y <- data$response

#drop predictor variable from dataset
data <- select(data, -response,-Class, -gender, -Genotype)

#set trainControl with customizable arguments
cv <- trainControl(method='cv',verboseIter=T, classProbs=TRUE)
#method boot, repeatedcv, repeated training/test splits, etc.
#verboseIter prints a training log
#classProbs class probablities are computed for classification models in each resample

caret models, including xgBoost

  • pro: large variety of models (https://topepo.github.io/caret/modelList.html)
  • pro: test a handful all at once and compare
  • con: depending on tuning parameters, can take a while to run
  • focus here on eXtreme Gradient Boosting = xgbTree or xgbLinear
    • (Stochastic Gradient Boosting = gbm & Random Forest = rf)
    • supports regression, classification, and ranking
    • it’s fast & accepts sparse input
    • http://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/latest/R-package/xgboostPresentation.html

caret modeling using train

let’s check our accuracy

accuracy <- names(models) %>%          # For each model name,
  lapply(function(model.name) {        # apply a function that will use that name to
    models[[model.name]]$resample %>%  # fetch a data frame containing cross validation accuracy,
      mutate(Model=model.name)         # attach the model name to that data frame,
  }) %>% do.call(rbind, .)            # and then merge results for all models together

#credit: Eric Czech

we’ve got a leak

colors <- c('#b2182b','#ef8a62','#fddbc7','#d1e5f0','#67a9cf','#2166ac')
#[from ColorBrewer: http://colorbrewer2.org/#type=diverging&scheme=RdBu&n=6]

#plot our iterations
accuracy %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Model, y=Accuracy, color=Model)) + 
  geom_jitter(width=.3) + 
  ggtitle('Cross-Validation Accuracy') + scale_color_manual(values=colors)

Feature Importance

  • pro: automatically select the features that are most relevant
  • pro: automatically calculated for caret models, including rf, gbm, and xgboost
  • pro: highlight an unexpected feature
  • con: list can be difficult to interpret

Partial Dependence

  • pro: INTERPRETABILITY
  • pro: understand new relationships in the data
  • con: can be misleading with higher-order hidden interactions
  • pro/con: more difficult to reduce down to a sound-bite

plot partial dependence

#set plot boxes
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
#set color, line width, and supress the box around the plot
par(col=colors[6], lwd=3, bty="n")
#plot the partial dependence
plot(models2[['gbm']]$finalModel, 'TRAIL_R3', type="response")
plot(models2[['gbm']]$finalModel, 'Beta_2_Microglobulin', type="response")
plot(models2[['gbm']]$finalModel, 'Thrombopoietin', type="response")
plot(models2[['gbm']]$finalModel, 'Ferritin', type="response")

point of it all

  • easy, painless process to quickly get to know your data in a different light
  • great for inspiration
  • great when you don’t need a “perfect” model
